05149nam a22008295i 9780824862558DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20012001hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029836929  a(OCoLC)1032695741  a(OCoLC)1037912642  a(OCoLC)1041991410  a(OCoLC)1046607343  a(OCoLC)1047005863  a(OCoLC)1049631332  a(OCoLC)1054866749  a97808248625587 a10.1515/97808248625582doi  a(DE-B1597)483923  a(OCoLC)1024022487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aREL0180002bisacsh0486pa320qDE-10100aFocusing the Familiar :bA Translation and Philosophical Interpretation of the Zhongyong /ced. by Roger T. Ames, David L. Hall. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: A Philosophical Interpretation of the Zhongyong -- tGlossary of Key Terms -- tFocusing the Familiar: A Translation of the Zhongyong -- tAppendix -- tBibliography of Works Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Zhongyong--translated here as Focusing the Familiar--has been regarded as a document of enormous wisdom for more than two millennia and is one of Confucianism's most sacred and seminal texts. It achieved truly canonical preeminence when it became one of the Four Books compiled and annotated by the Southern Song dynasty philosopher Zhu Xi (1130-1200). Within the compass of world literature, the influence of these books (Analects of Confucius, Great Learning, Zhongyong, and Mencius) on the Sinitic world of East Asia has been no less than the Bible and the Qu'ran on Western civilization. With this new translation David Hall and Roger Ames provide a distinctly philosophical interpretation of the Zhongyong, remaining attentive to the semantic and conceptual nuances of the text to account for its central place within classical Chinese literature. They present the text in such a way as to provide Western philosophers and other intellectuals access to a set of interpretations and arguments that offer new insights into issues and concerns common to both Chinese and Western thinkers. In addition to the annotated translation, a glossary of terms gives in concise form important senses of the terms that play a key role in the argument of the Zhongyong. An appendix addresses some of the more technical issues relevant to the understanding of both the history of the text and the history of its English translations. Here the translators introduce readers to the best contemporary textual studies of the Zhongyong and make use of the most recent archaeological discoveries in China to place the work within its own intellectual context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPhilosophy, ConfucianvEarly works to 1800. 0aPhilosophy, Confucian. 7aRELIGION / Confucianism.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T.1 aAmes, Roger T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHall, David L.1 aHall, David L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486255840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824862558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824862558.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Pack